Teacher's Remarks:
The post is correct in stating that "Lumad" is a Cebuano term for native, but falsely claims that this term is "not wat our IPs use to identify themselves" and that "CPP-NDF-NPA appropriated the term to lump all IPs into one identity & culture for propaganda & to better control them"

Anthropologist Gus Gatmaytan, Director of the Ateneo de Davao University‚Äôs Institute, said it can be argued that ‚Äúthe gradual adoption of the name Lumad is an agentive act on the part of the various groups in Mindanao, reflecting a realization that as a group they had similar histories, problems and aspirations, which together serve as the basis for a shared sense of identity; an identity which they chose to refer to as Lumad.‚Äù

Their continuing use of the name Lumad, he added, is ‚Äúan exercise of their right to self-ascription, which is itself rooted in their fundamental right to self-determination.‚Äù

Marites ‚ÄúMatet‚Äù Gonzalo, a Tagakolu anthropologist from Davao Occidental who serves as Coordinator of the two community-based IP schools of the Malita Tagakaulo Mission ‚Äî the Holy Cross of Malita‚Äôs Kyasan and Lebleb branches ‚Äî told MindaNews on Thursday that they have no issue with the word ‚ÄúLumad‚Äù because they use the term ‚Äúreferring to ourselves‚Äù when they talk to those outside their communities.

Teacher's Remarks:
‚ÄúLumad,‚Äù a term recognized by Philippine law, is a Cebuano Visayan word for ‚Äúnative‚Äù that is recorded in the 1972 dictionary of Cebuano Visayan by John Wolff, a professor emeritus of linguistics at Cornell University. A copy of the dictionary entry was shared with VERA Files Fact Check by medical anthropologist Michael Tan, former chancellor of the University of the Philippines Diliman.

The term was adopted by 15 of at least 18 ‚Äúethnic groups‚Äù in Mindanao that are neither Moro nor Christian in an assembly 34 years ago, based on a 2015 article published on the website of the National Commission for Culture and the Arts.

Marites ‚ÄúMatet‚Äù Gonzalo, a Tagakolu anthropologist from Davao Occidental who serves as Coordinator of the two community-based IP schools of the Malita Tagakaulo Mission ‚Äî the Holy Cross of Malita‚Äôs Kyasan and Lebleb branches ‚Äî told MindaNews on Thursday that they have no issue with the word ‚ÄúLumad‚Äù because they use the term ‚Äúreferring to ourselves‚Äù when they talk to those outside their communities.

The Alternative Learning Center for Agricultural and Livelihood Development (ALCADEV) is a Lumad school located in Surigao del Sur. It provides an agriculture-focused education and teaches indigenous students about sustainable farming practices. The school is privately-operated, but government-regulated.

In 2021, a claim that the ALCADEV was teaching Lumad students to become NPA members was made based on a photo which showed students holding makeshift guns. This claim was debunked as the photo was from a theater performance in 2017 portraying the deaths of Lumad leaders. A similar claim was made and debunked in 2020 after photos of Lumad students holding makeshift guns circulated online. These photos were, however, also taken from a 2019 skit where the students acted out the deaths of Lumad farmers.

The Alternative Learning Center for Agricultural and Livelihood Development (ALCADEV) is a Lumad school located in Surigao del Sur. It provides an agriculture-focused education and teaches indigenous students about sustainable farming practices. The school is privately-operated, but government-regulated.

The Salugpongan Ta Tanu Igkanogon Community Learning Center, Inc. (STTICLCI) is a formal learning institution established in 2007 to provide basic education to the Manobo. It was granted a permit to operate by DepEd from 2007 to 2018. In 2019, 55 Salugpongan schools were shut down based on unverified claims that they do not follow the DepEd curriculum and were teaching ideologies that advocate against the government.

Teacher's Remarks:
The Salugpongan Ta Tanu Igkanogon Community Learning Center, Inc. (STTICLCI) is a formal learning institution established in 2007 to provide basic education to the Manobo. It was granted a permit to operate by DepEd from 2007 to 2018. In 2019, 55 Salugpongan schools were shut down based on unverified claims that they do not follow the DepEd curriculum and were teaching ideologies that advocate against the government.

Lumad schools have faced various attacks such as forced closures, illegal arrests, and aerial bombings based on accusations that they are training centers for NPA communist rebels. These claims, however, remain unfounded without substantial pieces and due process as confirmed by the CHR.

Contrary to claims that Lumad schools teach students how to become NPA members, these schools actually teach numeracy, literacy in English and Filipino, history, skills such as carpentry and sewing, and the practice of scientific and sustainable agriculture. They follow DepEd‚Äôs Alternative Learning System Accreditation and Equivalency Test to assess learners who are not under a formal education system.

Teacher's Remarks:
The Alternative Learning Center for Agricultural and Livelihood Development (ALCADEV) is a Lumad school located in Surigao del Sur. It provides an agriculture-focused education and teaches indigenous students about sustainable farming practices. The school is privately-operated, but government-regulated.

In 2021, a claim that the ALCADEV was teaching Lumad students to become NPA members was made based on a photo which showed students holding makeshift guns. This claim was debunked as the photo was from a theater performance in 2017 portraying the deaths of Lumad leaders. A similar claim was made and debunked in 2020 after photos of Lumad students holding makeshift guns circulated online. These photos were, however, also taken from a 2019 skit where the students acted out the deaths of Lumad farmers.

‚ÄúLumad,‚Äù a term recognized by Philippine law, is a Cebuano Visayan word for ‚Äúnative‚Äù that is recorded in the 1972 dictionary of Cebuano Visayan by John Wolff, a professor emeritus of linguistics at Cornell University. A copy of the dictionary entry was shared with VERA Files Fact Check by medical anthropologist Michael Tan, former chancellor of the University of the Philippines Diliman.

The term was adopted by 15 of at least 18 ‚Äúethnic groups‚Äù in Mindanao that are neither Moro nor Christian in an assembly 34 years ago, based on a 2015 article published on the website of the National Commission for Culture and the Arts.

Some of these bakwit schools were established in UP Cebu in October 2019, St. Scholastica‚Äôs Academy Cebu in January 2020, and University of San Carlos (USC) in March 2020. ‚ÄúLumad,‚Äù a term recognized by Philippine law, is a Cebuano Visayan word for ‚Äúnative‚Äù that is recorded in the 1972 dictionary of Cebuano Visayan by John Wolff, a professor emeritus of linguistics at Cornell University. A copy of the dictionary entry was shared with VERA Files Fact Check by medical anthropologist Michael Tan, former chancellor of the University of the Philippines Diliman.

The term was adopted by 15 of at least 18 ‚Äúethnic groups‚Äù in Mindanao that are neither Moro nor Christian in an assembly 34 years ago, based on a 2015 article published on the website of the National Commission for Culture and the Arts.

Marites ‚ÄúMatet‚Äù Gonzalo, a Tagakolu anthropologist from Davao Occidental who serves as Coordinator of the two community-based IP schools of the Malita Tagakaulo Mission ‚Äî the Holy Cross of Malita‚Äôs Kyasan and Lebleb branches ‚Äî stated that they have no issue with the word ‚ÄúLumad‚Äù because they use the term ‚Äúreferring to ourselves‚Äù when they talk to those outside their communities.

The Alternative Learning Center for Agricultural and Livelihood Development (ALCADEV) is a Lumad school located in Surigao del Sur. It provides an agriculture-focused education and teaches indigenous students about sustainable farming practices. The school is privately-operated, but government-regulated.

In 2021, a claim that the ALCADEV was teaching Lumad students to become NPA members was made based on a photo which showed students holding makeshift guns. This claim was debunked as the photo was from a theater performance in 2017 portraying the deaths of Lumad leaders. A similar claim was made and debunked in 2020 after photos of Lumad students holding makeshift guns circulated online. These photos were, however, also taken from a 2019 skit where the students acted out the deaths of Lumad farmers.

‚ÄúLumad,‚Äù a term recognized by Philippine law, is a Cebuano Visayan word for ‚Äúnative‚Äù that is recorded in the 1972 dictionary of Cebuano Visayan by John Wolff, a professor emeritus of linguistics at Cornell University. A copy of the dictionary entry was shared with VERA Files Fact Check by medical anthropologist Michael Tan, former chancellor of the University of the Philippines Diliman.

The term was adopted by 15 of at least 18 ‚Äúethnic groups‚Äù in Mindanao that are neither Moro nor Christian in an assembly 34 years ago, based on a 2015 article published on the website of the National Commission for Culture and the Arts.

Marites ‚ÄúMatet‚Äù Gonzalo, a Tagakolu anthropologist from Davao Occidental who serves as Coordinator of the two community-based IP schools of the Malita Tagakaulo Mission ‚Äî the Holy Cross of Malita‚Äôs Kyasan and Lebleb branches ‚Äî stated that they have no issue with the word ‚ÄúLumad‚Äù because they use the term ‚Äúreferring to ourselves‚Äù when they talk to those outside their communities.

[https://verafiles.org/articles/vera-files-fact-check-badoy-denies-existence-lumad-falsely-c]

There have been many allegations of child trafficking with the intention of training them for the NPA, using Lumad schools as fronts for their training centers. In support of these claims, the PNP organized ‚Äòrescue operations‚Äô in order to ‚Äòsave‚Äô the children from indoctrination. In 2021, 19 Lumad children were ‚Äòrescued‚Äô by the PNP after claims of being kidnapped to be indoctrinated into the NPA. However, upon interviewing the rescued children, they claim they were taught reading and writing instead of warfare training. 

In addition, contrary to claims that Lumad schools teach students how to become NPA members, these schools actually teach numeracy, literacy in English and Filipino, history, skills such as carpentry and sewing, and the practice of scientific and sustainable agriculture. They follow DepEd‚Äôs Alternative Learning System Accreditation and Equivalency Test to assess learners who are not under a formal education system.
